{{short description|US environmental modeling software company}} {{Infobox company | name = Aquaveo, LLC | logo = Aquaveo Logo.png | logo_size = 200px | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | key_people = {{hlist|Alan Zundel|Norm Jones|Royd Nelson|Jim Nelson}} | foundation = April 2007 | location = [[Provo, Utah]] | industry = [[Hydrogeology]] [[software]] | homepage = {{url|http://www.aquaveo.com|Aquaveo.com}} }}
'''Aquaveo''' is an environmental and water resources [[Computer simulation|modeling software]] company based in [[Provo, Utah]] that develops software used to model and simulate [[groundwater]], [[Drainage basin|watershed]], and [[surface water]] resources.<ref name="ubique 20150529"/> Its main software products include SMS, GMS, WMS, and Arc Hydro Groundwater.
==History== The Engineering Computer Graphics Laboratory (ECGL) was established in 1985 at [[Brigham Young University]].<ref name="ecgl 19990421">{{cite web|url=http://emrl.byu.edu/|title=Environmental Modeling Research Laboratory|publisher=Engineering Computer Graphics Laboratory at [[Brigham Young University]]|accessdate=March 5, 2018|archivedate=April 21, 1999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990421051442/http://emrl.byu.edu/}}</ref> Simulation data produced in the lab was critical to ''[[Anderson v. Cryovac, Inc.]]'', a 1986 federal lawsuit concerning toxic contamination of groundwater in [[Woburn, Massachusetts]].<ref name="desnews 19990402">{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/689128/Software-keeps-an-eye-on-invisible-water.html?pg=all |title=Software keeps an eye on 'invisible' water: Provo product monitors ground supply |first=Jerry |last=Spangler |date=2 April 1999 |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |accessdate=25 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fZJi3eUR?url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/689128/Software-keeps-an-eye-on-invisible-water.html?pg=all |archivedate=25 February 2016 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> After using another BYU product—Movie BYU—to animate a hydrology problem to make it easier to understand, Norm Jones decided to start work on software that helped engineers visualize problems and solutions.<ref name="byumag fall 2002"/> Use of the tools created by Jones allowed the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] to save "hundreds of thousands of dollars."<ref name="byumag fall 2002"/>
Alan Zundel and James Nelson, two other professors at BYU, also became involved in the process of developing the software in 1991.<ref name="byumag fall 2002"/> By 2002, the company's software was being used in "more than 100 countries and [by] more than 9,000 organizations."<ref name="byumag fall 2002"/> Royd Nelson created Environmental Modeling Systems (EMSI), a private company, in October 1995 to distribute the software created in the ECGL.<ref name="entity emsi">{{cite web|url=https://secure.utah.gov/bes/details.html?entity=1284924-0142 |title=Entity Search: Environmental Modeling Systems Incorporated |publisher=Division of Corporations and Commercial Code on Utah.gov |accessdate=25 February 2016 |date=29 September 2015 |archivedate=25 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fZKRH8Ih?url=https://secure.utah.gov/bes/details.html?entity=1284924-0142 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> The name of the lab was changed in September 1998 to the Environmental Modeling Research Laboratory (EMRL).<ref name="ecgl 19990421"/>
The government of [[India]] used early versions of the software developed by the EMRL to help with finding sources of clean groundwater, setting groundwater policy, and setting a course of action to clean up the contaminated groundwater in their country.<ref name="desnews 19990402"/> State and local governments in Utah and California have used the software to help trace contaminant sources at farms and mining facilities, and to determine how to manage water resources in drier climates like the Los Angeles area.<ref name="desnews 19990402"/>
The planners of the [[2002 Winter Olympics]], held in Salt Lake City, Utah, used the [[Watershed Modeling System]] (WMS) software to simulate terrorist attacks on water infrastructure such as the [[Jordanelle Reservoir]].<ref name="byumag fall 2002">{{cite web|url=http://magazine.byu.edu/article/modeling-the-worlds-waters/ |title=Modeling the World’s Waters |first=Nathan K. |last=Chai |publisher=''[[BYU Magazine]]'' |date=Fall 2002 |accessdate=25 February 2016 |archivedate=25 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fZPVKbl2?url=http://magazine.byu.edu/article/modeling-the-worlds-waters/ |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> In April 2007, a private company named Aquaveo was created to develop the work of the EMRL as commercial products, and the main people at the lab moved to the new company.<ref name="ubique 20150529"/><ref name="emrl">{{cite web|url=http://emrl.byu.edu/ |title=The Environmental Modeling Research Laboratory |publisher=[[Brigham Young University]] |date=3 May 2012 |accessdate=9 September 2013 |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQCLUwKg?url=http://emrl.byu.edu/ |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref name="aquaveo-about">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/about-us |title=About Us |publisher=Aquaveo |accessdate=6 August 2013 |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQCahpfD?url=http://www.aquaveo.com/about-us |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> EMSI and Aquaveo merged in October 2008, keeping the company name of "Aquaveo".<ref name="merge">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/merge |title=EMS-I is now Aquaveo! |publisher=Aquaveo |accessdate=25 February 2016 |archivedate=25 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fZLxyGJT?url=http://www.aquaveo.com/merge |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
Local and federal government agencies, including the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|US Army Corps of Engineers]], the [[Federal Highway Administration|US Federal Highway Administration]], [[Government of Los Angeles County|Los Angeles County]], the [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]], the [[United States Department of Energy|US Department of Energy]], and the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|USEPA]], have software and consulting contracts with Aquaveo. In 2011, the government of Australia used Arc Hydro Groundwater to help in developing a national groundwater information system.<ref name="esri australia 2011">{{cite web|url=http://www.esri.com/news/arcnews/summer11articles/australia-develops-a-national-groundwater-information-system.html |title=Australia Develops a National Groundwater Information System |publisher=[[Esri]] |date=2011 |accessdate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQGEgX4i?url=http://www.esri.com/news/arcnews/summer11articles/australia-develops-a-national-groundwater-information-system.html |archivedate=19 February 2016 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> Arc Hydro was used to convert bore and construction log data and to create geovolumes from georasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=ftp://ftp.bom.gov.au/anon/home/water/ngis/NgisProductSpec.pdf |title=National Groundwater Information System: Data Product Specification, version 1.2 |format=PDF |date=April 2015 |accessdate=19 February 2016 |publisher= |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQI6tnsR?url=ftp://ftp.bom.gov.au/anon/home/water/ngis/NgisProductSpec.pdf |pages=22–23 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
Aquaveo worked with the [[Office of Naval Research]], the [[Carderock Division of the Naval Surface Warfare Center|Carderock Division]] of the [[Naval Surface Warfare Center]], and several universities and companies to create the Environmental and Ship Motion Forecasting system.<ref name="military.com sep 2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/09/27/new-technology-could-impact-ships-at-sea.html |title=New Technology Could Impact Ships at Sea |first=David |last=Smalley |publisher=[[Military.com]] |date=27 September 2013 |accessdate=19 February 2016 |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQGzk5YM?url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/09/27/new-technology-could-impact-ships-at-sea.html |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> This system was designed to "provide sea-based forces with new capabilities for difficult operations like ship-to-ship transfer of personnel, vehicles or material-giving operators sea condition information at levels of accuracy never possible before."<ref name="military.com sep 2013"/>
==Products== Aquaveo is primarily a software development company for water modeling that allow water to be modeled in most situations: watershed, rivers, lakes, ocean tides, flooding, and so on. Its flagship products are SMS and GMS, which are used by municipalities and universities around the world. It also produces WMS and Arc Hydro Groundwater. Their software is used by "over 12,000 firms, government institutions, and universities in over 120 countries".<ref name="ubique 20150529">{{cite web|url=http://ubique.americangeo.org/company-spotlight/aquaveo-using-geospatial-modeling-to-map-surface-and-groundwater/ |title=Aquaveo: Using Geospatial Modeling to Map Surface and Groundwater |first=Christopher |last=Ewell |date=29 May 2015 |publisher=''Ubique: The [[American Geographical Society]] Newsletter'' |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQKV2Jcp?url=http://ubique.americangeo.org/company-spotlight/aquaveo-using-geospatial-modeling-to-map-surface-and-groundwater/ |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref name="aquaveo-about"/>
===Arc Hydro Groundwater=== Arc Hydro Groundwater allows for managing groundwater and subsurface data within [[ArcGIS]]. The software was created in cooperation with [[Environmental Systems Research Institute|ESRI]] to allow groundwater and subsurface analysis, as well as using MODFLOW to analyze results.<ref name="arc hydro intro">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/software/ahgw-archydro-groundwater-introduction|title=Arc Hydro Groundwater|publisher=Aquaveo|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
===GMS=== {{main|GMS (software)}}
The Groundwater Modeling System (GMS) is a computer application designed to build and simulate [[groundwater]] [[Computer model|models]]. It uses 2D and 3D [[geostatistics]] and [[stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] modeling to show how water and contaminants can move through various soil structures. The software supports many standard models, including [[MODFLOW]], MODPATH, MT3DMS, RT3D, FEMWATER, [[SEEP2D]], and [[UTEXAS]].<ref name="gms intro">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/software/gms-groundwater-modeling-system-introduction|title=Groundwater Modeling System Introduction|publisher=Aquaveo|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
===SMS=== {{main|SMS (hydrology software)}}
The Surface-water Modeling System (SMS) is an [[computer application|application]] used for building and simulating [[surface water]] [[Computer model|models]] within the [[hydrological cycle]], including river and stream flow models, flooding, and sediment and particle flow in lakes and oceans. It features 1D and 2D conceptual modeling. The software supports standard models, including [[ADCIRC]], CMS-FLOW2D, FESWMS, TABS, TUFLOW, BOUSS-2D, CGWAVE, STWAVE, CMS-WAVE (WABED), GENESIS, and PTM.<ref name="sms intro">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/software/sms-surface-water-modeling-system-introduction|title=SMS Introduction|publisher=Aquaveo|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
===WMS=== {{main|WMS (hydrology software)}}
The Watershed Modeling System (WMS) is an application used for developing [[drainage basin|watershed]] [[Computer model|simulations]] of river hydraulics, municipal storm drain systems, floodplains, and watersheds. WMS supports [[Lumped parameters|lumped parameter]], [[Regression analysis|regression]], and 2D [[Hydrology|hydrologic]] modeling of watersheds, and can be used to model both water quantity and [[water quality]]. It supports standard models such as [[HEC-1]], [[HEC-RAS]], [[HEC-HMS]], TR-20, TR-55 hydrologic model, National Flood Frequency Model, rational hydrologic model, MODRAT, HSPF, CE-QUAL-W2, [[GSSHA]], and SMPDBK.<ref name="wms intro">{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaveo.com/software/wms-watershed-modeling-system-introduction|title=WMS Introduction|publisher=Aquaveo|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>
==Associations== Aquaveo is a member of the [[American Water Resources Association]].<ref name="awra assoc">{{cite web|url=http://www.awra.org/memberservices/member.php?action=detail&id=158 |title=Aquaveo |publisher=[[American Water Resources Association]] |accessdate=19 February 2016 |archivedate=19 February 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fQGmAA3v?url=http://www.awra.org/memberservices/member.php?action=detail&id=158 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>
